The number of events is Poisson-distributed with mean
\code{time_horizon * n_particles * branching_rate}. After the last event,
particles are propagated to time \code{time_horizon}, so
\code{max(result$times)} always equals \code{time_horizon}.

\strong{Position tracking:} Instead of overwriting killed particles in-place,
each kill event stores the killed particle's death position and appends a
new column for the offspring. This eliminates false diagonal lines in
particle path plots.

When \code{path_resolution} is set, each inter-event interval \verb{[t_i, t_\{i+1\}]}
is split into \verb{ceiling((t_\{i+1\} - t_i) / path_resolution)} equal sub-steps.
The final propagation to \code{time_horizon} is sub-stepped as well.
Intermediate rows have \code{is_event = FALSE}.
